
If schools could keep good teachers a few years longer and push bad ones out the door a few years earlier, "you'd start a revolution," says Eric A. Hanushek, an education policy expert at Stanford University. The governor of Massachusetts may be planting the seeds of that revolution with his controversial new plan to institute merit and incentive pay for teachers Of course, by proposing to pay more to math and science teachers and to reward teachers who raise student performance with generous bonuses, Republican Gov. Mitt Romney is making enemies of traditional teacher unions. 

